<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Alkali Resistance" class="currentChild" href="Alkali_Resistance">Alkali Resistance</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A property of paper describing its ability to resist fading, discoloring, or deteriorating when exposed to alkaline (low-<a title="pH" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/pH">pH</a>) substances such as soaps and adhesives. Alkali resistance is an important property when a paper is intended to be used in the packaging of such materials. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
The term <em>alkali resistance</em> also refers to a similar ability of a printing ink to resist <a title="Bleeding" href="Bleeding">bleeding</a>, discoloring, fading, or chemically reacting with alkaline materials. Inks intended for use in the packaging of soaps or other alkaline materials need to possess high alkali resistance. (See <a title="Pigment" href="Pigment">Pigment</a>.) (See also <a title="Soap Resistance" href="Soap_Resistance">Soap Resistance</a>.) 
</p>
